title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch HK41 .308 w/HK Accessories
postcontent: Scarce, highly collectable Heckler & Koch HK41 .308 caliber semi-auto rifle. Very few imported into the United States; all were imported in 1966 by the Santa Fe Division of the Golden State Arms Corp. It is estimated that fewer than 400 rifle were produced and only a portion of these were imported to the U.S. The first generation HK41 has the G3 style "paddle" magazine release (in addition to the standard side release), and also features the lower push pin hole that was originally inteded for attachment of the selective fire G3 trigger group. There featuresmade it too easy to illegally convert the rifle to full auto and were deleted in the later production HK41 and HK91 rifles. First generation HK41 rifle were "grandfathered" by the ATF, and are legal to own in their orginal configuaration. Condition: NRA Excellant. All numbers match, bright bore. Very minor handling marks, scratches. Original HK Accessories: Nine Magazines, Bi-Pod, Bayonet w/sheath and case, Two Slings-1 leather/1 Cotton, Sight Tool, Small Parts Kit, Extra Flash Hider, Magazine Loader, Original Owners Manual, Assorted HK Literature

title: For Sale:  Original Knight DISC .50 Caliber rifle
postcontent:
This is an original Knight DISC .50cal rifle.  This model shoots with the orange primers, it has not been altered to the 209 system.  However, you can buy the Priming loader from Knights in a bulk 100 pack for $13 that allows you to shoot 209 shotgun primers as it is currently setup.  There is also a conversion kit available from Knight to convert it to the newer DISC Extreme for $125.  The absolute cheapest of the new DISC Extreme line has an MSRP of $559, and some of the more fancy models get to near $1000.  I'm not suggesting this is worth that, just a tidbit of info for those who are interested in getting into Black Powder weapons.  This gun doesn't appear to have been used very much, however the original owner most obviously didn't clean it after the last use and there is some rusty crud in a few spots down the barrel, and a spot on the crown of the barrel.  I ran a cleaning rod through it, and got a good bit of it out with little effort. (there is some pitting)  I have been told by some of the folks on the Black Powder forums that rust in this particular gun is common.  They suggested a couple cleaning methods to me, but I don't want to take it down that far and do the work, so I'll just sell it for a lower price and the buyer can take it down and clean to their hearts extent.

The scope is a Tasco WA3-9x40TV.  It is far from a high end optic, however I did take it out and check it, it's clear with no fog or scratching.  A great starter scope.

Price is $175, cash only no trades.  I can ship this directly to buyers house as this gun is not restricted through the delivery systems.  It will weigh about 12 pounds in box.  Email me with any questions, I'll do my best to answer them, but I'm by no means a Black Powder shooter and know little about  them.

Also, I have another BP rifle listed here on armslist currently, as well as a .44cal 1858 Remington New Army Revolver replica from Uberti.  If a local buyer wishes to come see it in person, I will show it at Bullseye Marksman Gun Club in Cumming, and only there.  They are located just off GA400 exit 13.

title: Want To Buy:  No More Assault Weapon Ban Madness Prices
postcontent: Enough is enough people.  For the last 3 months prices on firearms and ammunition have been outrageous.  Those of who are demanding ridiculous premiums for your firearms have every right to do so, but the panic buying days are over.  I understand supply and demand has an affect on prices, but that does not justify someone asking well over msrp prices for firearms that wouldn't even be affected by an assault weapon ban.  If you are new to the firearms world I urge you to do research and shop around before you are taken advantage of by a private seller here or anywhere else.  Things are slowly but surely getting back to normal.  Stop panic buying and do not overpay.
